					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Speak of the devil... Adobe Media Encoder decided to crap out and return a smudged output (maybe my 16x24 animation was too small or something, there's no preferences for this behaviour). I rebuilt the project in PS:s timeline editor - it crashed and won't behave after that (probably need to restart/clear memory).  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_evil.gif" alt=":evil:" title="Evil or Very Mad" /> <br /><br />After a bit of toiling, i found a better solution with the tools i have:<br /><br />1)After Effects: add to render qeue. <br />2)Export as QuickTime .mov, draft quality, go.<br />3)Open in Photoshop<br />4)Save for the web (legacy); gif. It even retains the pixel sharpness when i goof around and scale it, so hooray!  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /> <br /><br />It took a while to figure out but that proved much quicker and a lot more trusty in terms of result. Sharing animation sequences won't be a hassle anymore. <br /><br />That said, aseprite looks like a nice addition. The free beta was a bit lacking, but i can see how it encourages a more fluid style of animation.</div>

					
